The Codes of the Kings are suffi- ciently explicit on the subJect of Tedm, to render no investigation of this word necessary: its grant by charter may he admitted at once. Toll however is not found in the same collections, at least not by name, and it is therefore desirahle to show that at an early period it was matter of grant.

In the charters of the Saxons as well as the Nor- mans, this word has a twofold force; it denotes as well exemption from payment ol toll, as the right· to levy toll, privileges which after the conquest were held to be inseparable from one another. Whether this principle prevailed before the time of the Nor- mans 1 cannot positivcly say; but evidence can be given of granta by which the exemption from toll was given, as well of grants which conferred the right of levying it.
